The classic example of this algorithm is to search for a value in a sorted list. Instead of checking each element of the list, we can choose the middle element and compare it to the value we want to find. If it turns out to be greater than that value, then we discard the right half of the list. If it is less, then we discard the left half of the list. We continue repeating this process until the list we are searching in has only one element.

Since this algorithm halves the number of candidates in each iteration, its time complexity is O(log n) where n is the initial length of the list. An example implementation would be:

```Python
def binary_search(arr: list, value: int):
    left = 0
    right = len(arr) - 1
    while left <= right:
        mid = left + (right - left) // 2
        if arr[mid] < value:
            left = mid + 1
        else:
            right = mid - 1
    if arr[left] == value:
        return True
    return False
```

